4 A BILL
5 TO BE ENTITLED
6 AN ACT
7
8 Relating to geographic information technology; to add
9 Chapter 27A, commencing with Section 41-27A-1, to Title 41 of
10 the Code of Alabama 1975, to establish the Alabama Geographic
11 Information Executive Council, the Alabama Geographic
12 Information Program Office, the State of Alabama Geographic
13 Information Officer, and an advisory committee; and to provide
14 for coordination between the Alabama Geographic Information
15 Executive Council and Alabama Geographic Information Program
16 Office with the 911 Board; to amend Section 11-98-4.1, Code of
17 Alabama 1975, to further provide for the authority of the 911
18 Board to compile and maintain geographic information system
19 data for emergency 911 services; and to make nonsubstantive,
20 technical revisions to update existing code language to
21 current style.
22 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
23 Section 1. Chapter 27A, commencing with Section
24 41-27A-1, is added to Title 41 of the Code of Alabama 1975, to
25 read as follows:
26 §41-27A-1
27 The Legislature finds all of the following:
28 (1) The development, use, and sharing of geographic
Page 1

(1) The development, use, and sharing of geographic
HB97 Engrossed
29 information, geospatial data, and the efficient use of
30 geographic information system (GIS) technology are yielding
31 sustained, long-term benefits to the people of Alabama, with
32 innumerable applications that serve economic development,
33 enhance governmental operations, protect natural resources,
34 and simplify human activity.
35 (2) Because public agencies expend considerable
36 resources collecting and managing geographic information in
37 diverse formats and scales, it is necessary to require
38 coordination and direction in the development and
39 implementation of GIS to continually improve the delivery of
40 public services, to reduce redundancy and duplication of
41 effort, and to prevent the spread of erroneous geographic
42 information in activities that demand urgency such as
43 emergency response.
44 (3) The management and coordination of GIS is currently
45 entrusted to the Alabama Geographic Information Executive
46 Council, the Alabama Geographic Information Program Office,
47 and the Advisory Committee, all created by executive order.
48 (4) The 911 Board, and by extension the local emergency
49 communication districts, are charged by legislative act with
50 the "efficient and effective delivery" of enhanced 911
51 service, a duty that explicitly requires the collection and
52 remediation of geospatial information into GIS mapping.
53 (5) The Legislature wishes to enable formal
54 coordination between the Alabama Geographic Information
55 Program Office, as the operating arm of the Alabama Geographic
56 Information Executive Council, and the 911 Board, while
Page 2

Information Executive Council, and the 911 Board, while
HB97 Engrossed
57 maintaining the boundaries of their authorized duties and
58 functions.
59 §41-27A-2
60 (a) The Alabama Geographic Information Executive
61 Council (Executive Council) is established as an independent
62 council to develop policies regarding the use of geographic
63 information, geographic information systems (GIS), and other
64 related technologies, to include all of the following
65 responsibilities:
66 (1) Strategic planning for a sustainable state program
67 for GIS.
68 (2) Resolution of policy and technology issues.
69 (3) Coordination of interagency development of a high
70 quality, accurate framework for geospatial data.
71 (4) Coordination, direction, and facilitation of state,
72 county, and local government GIS efforts.
73 (5) Development of educational outreach to coordinate
74 geospatial training initiatives.
75 (6) Provision of advice to the Governor, Legislature,
76 and local governing bodies on needed direction,
77 responsibilities, and funding regarding geospatial
78 information.
79 (7) Evaluation and determination of staffing
80 requirements for GIS coordination at the state level.
81 (8) Solicitation of input from all stakeholders at all
82 levels of government and the private sector, including public
83 utilities, business professionals, industry leaders, and
84 others with a vested interest in GIS.
