117 (2) Appointments to the Executive Council shall be
118 coordinated to assure that council membership is inclusive and
119 reflects the racial, gender, geographic, urban, rural, and
120 economic diversity of the state.
121 (3) Members shall serve terms that coincide with their
122 respective offices or appointments. No individual shall
123 continue to serve on the Executive Council when he or she, or
124 if applicable, the designating officer, no longer serves in
125 the office to which he or she was elected or appointed.
126 (4) The Governor shall designate a Chair from the
127 membership.
128 (5) The Executive Council shall meet at the call of the
129 Chair and proceedings shall be subject to state law and
130 administrative procedure.
131 (6) The Executive Council may subdivide itself into
132 standing committees and work groups to accomplish its
133 responsibilities.
134 (7) Members shall serve without compensation and be
135 reimbursed by their respective departments or agencies or, if
136 applicable, according to the policy of their respective
137 organizations.
138 §41-27A-3
139 (a) The Alabama Geographic Information Program Office
140 (GIS Office) is established to be the operating arm of the
Page 5

(GIS Office) is established to be the operating arm of the
HB97 Engrossed
141 Executive Council. Except as provided in Section 41-27A-5, the
142 GIS Office shall be the sole instrumentality of the state for
143 coordination of geographic information, GIS, and other
144 geospatial-related technologies by all state departments and
145 agencies or state-funded entities.
146 (b) The GIS Office shall be a division in the Alabama
147 State Law Enforcement Agency (ALEA), which shall provide
148 administrative services for the GIS office.
149 (c)(1) The GIS Office shall be managed by a director,
150 who shall be the Geographic Information Officer (GIO), who
151 shall be appointed by the Secretary of the Alabama State Law
152 Enforcement Agency and employed in the classified service of
153 the Merit System.
154 (2) The GIO shall be assisted by a deputy, who shall be
155 appointed by the Secretary of the Alabama State Law
156 Enforcement Agency and employed in the classified service of
157 the Merit System.
158 (3) The GIO shall manage the GIS Office subject to the
159 policies, standards, guidance, and instruction of the
160 Executive Council.
161 (d) The GIS Office shall identify, plan, and implement
162 the most efficient and effective means to use and integrate
163 geographic information as a strategic management resource, to
164 include all of the following duties:
165 (1) Identify duplicative geospatial acquisitions,
166 initiatives, and operations across state government and
167 recommend efforts to minimize duplication of such activities.
168 (2) Maintain a master index of all geographic
Page 6

(2) Maintain a master index of all geographic
HB97 Engrossed
169 information maintained by any political subdivision of the
170 state or other state-funded entity.
171 (3) Maintain a central repository and data services for
172 the storage of, or access to, any geographic information that
173 may be lawfully used for state or for local government
174 geospatial-related operations or for any lawful private sector
175 activity.
176 (4) Assist government operations with implementation of
177 state geospatial standards as adopted by the Executive
178 Council.
179 (5) Through ALEA, coordinate procurements, pool funds,
180 negotiate and enter into contracts or memoranda of
181 understanding in furtherance of GIS Office duties.
182 (6) Provide administrative and technical support to the
183 Executive Council.
184 (e)(1) The GIS Office may receive funds from the State
185 General Fund or Education Trust Fund which are appropriated by
186 the Legislature for the purposes provided in this chapter,
187 subject to any law governing any expenditure of appropriations
188 from the State General Fund or Education Trust Fund.
189 (2) The GIS Office may receive gifts, grants, and any
190 other funding available by law and may recoup costs for
191 services rendered or other expenditures directly related to
192 the duties enumerated in subsection (d).
193 (3) The GIS Office shall provide, upon request, an
194 accounting to ALEA of all funds expended, available,
195 committed, or encumbered.
196 §41-27A-4
Page 7

§41-27A-4
HB97 Engrossed
197 (a)(1) An Advisory Committee is established to ensure
198 that state and local interests are considered by the GIS
199 Executive Council.
200 (2) The Advisory Committee shall have all of the
201 following purposes:
202 a. Foster communication and cooperation among state,
203 local, and federal agencies, educational institutions, private
204 industry, and others concerning GIS.
205 b. Provide guidance and advice to the Executive Council
206 in the fulfillment of the council's responsibilities.
207 c. Promote discussion among stakeholders of GIS issues
208 relevant to the state and provide advice to the GIS community.
209 (b) The GIO shall serve as the Chair of the Advisory
210 Committee.
211 (c) The GIO shall select advisory committee members who
212 shall serve at the pleasure of the GIO. The GIO shall ensure
213 that the committee has a statewide representation of
214 stakeholders who are familiar with water resources, air
215 resources, agricultural resources, energy resources, cultural
216 resources, land resources, mineral resources, environmental
217 management, forestry, geology, health, local government,
218 planning, public safety, criminal justice, social services,
219 transportation, utilities, waste management, homeland
220 security, and wildlife management.
221 (d) The GIO may create subcommittees with defined
222 tasks, appoint, replace, or remove members of the
223 subcommittees, and abolish subcommittees.
224 §41-27A-5
Page 8

§41-27A-5
HB97 Engrossed
225 (a) In aid of the role and duties of the GIS Office as
226 the statewide coordinator and central repository for
227 geographic information pursuant to Section 41-27A-3, the 911
228 Board is recognized as the sole authority for the gathering,
229 remediation, and maintenance of geographic information for the
230 provision of emergency 911 services to the residents of
231 Alabama, pursuant to Section 11-98-4.1.
232 (b) The 911 Board shall regularly inform the Executive
233 Council and the GIO on its GIS data gathering and remediation
234 activities, GIS auditing and monitoring protocols, and
235 operational policies to ensure the utmost coordination between
236 the GIS Office and the 911 Board in similar or parallel tasks
237 and responsibilities to avoid duplication and enhance
238 uniformity in protocols, standards, data gathering,
239 maintenance, and storage wherever possible and efficient.
240 (c) Pursuant to its duties, the GIS Office shall
241 recognize the unique competence of the 911 Board and the local
242 emergency communication districts due to the critical function
243 of emergency response for which the 911 Board and the local
244 emergency communication districts are responsible.
